Geothermal energy is the [thermal energy](/Thermal_energy) humanity has the audacity to extract from the Earth's [crust](/Crust_(geology)). This planetary furnace is a cocktail of primordial heat left over from the violent formation of the planet and the incessant, slow-burning fire of [radioactive decay](/Radioactive_decay) from deep within its core. For millennia, we have been tapping into this deep heat, first for basic survival and comfort, and more recently, to power our insatiable electrical grid.

[Geothermal heating](/Geothermal_heating), which involves little more than channeling water from [hot springs](/Hot_springs), is an ancient practice. It has been used for bathing since the [Paleolithic](/Paleolithic) era—proving that even our earliest ancestors appreciated a good soak—and for sophisticated [space heating](/Space_heating) since the Roman Empire decided cold floors were beneath them. The leap to [geothermal power](/Geothermal_power), the actual generation of electricity, is a far more recent and ambitious endeavor, only truly getting underway in the 20th century. A key advantage, often touted by its proponents, is that geothermal plants churn out power at a constant, predictable rate, utterly indifferent to the whims of weather that plague solar and wind. In theory, the geothermal resources beneath our feet are more than sufficient to satisfy all of humanity's energy demands. In practice, most extraction is predictably clustered in the geologically unstable areas near [tectonic plate boundaries](/Tectonic_plate_boundaries).

The cost of generating this power saw a welcome decline of 25% through the 1980s and 1990s. Technological progress has continued to chip away at expenses, making more and more of the Earth's heat a viable resource. In a 2021 estimate, the US Department of Energy pegged the cost of power from a newly constructed plant at a rather competitive $0.05 per kilowatt-hour.

By 2019, the world had managed to install 13,900 [megawatts](/Megawatts) (MW) of geothermal power capacity. Beyond electricity, an additional 28 gigawatts of direct thermal energy were being used as of 2010 for applications like district heating, warming buildings, filling spas, driving industrial processes, desalination, and various agricultural uses. As of 2019, this quietly simmering industry employed roughly one hundred thousand people globally.

The term *geothermal* itself is a blunt portmanteau from the Greek roots γῆ (*gê*), meaning Earth, and θερμός (*thermós*), meaning hot. A description of elegant simplicity for a process of immense complexity.

### History

The oldest known pool fed by a hot spring, a relic from the [Qin dynasty](/Qin_dynasty) constructed in the 3rd century BC.

The use of [hot springs](/Hot_spring) for bathing is a practice so ancient it dates back to at least the [Paleolithic](/Paleolithic) period. The [oldest known spa](/Huaqing_Pool) is located at the site of the Huaqing Chi palace in China. In the first century CE, the ever-practical Romans conquered [Aquae Sulis](/Aquae_Sulis), which we now call [Bath, Somerset](/Bath,_Somerset), England. They promptly exploited the local hot springs to engineer elaborate [public baths](/Thermae) and an ingenious [underfloor heating](/Hypocaust) system. The admission fees they charged likely represent the first commercial exploitation of geothermal energy, a transactional relationship with the planet's heat that continues to this day.

The world's oldest geothermal district heating system, found in [Chaudes-Aigues](/Chaudes-Aigues), France, has been in continuous operation since the 15th century. The industrial age brought more ambitious applications. In 1827, resourceful industrialists began using [geyser](/Geyser) steam to extract [boric acid](/Boric_acid) from [volcanic mud](/Volcanic_mud) in [Larderello](/Larderello), Italy.

In 1892, America’s first [district heating](/District_heating) system was established in [Boise, Idaho](/Boise,_Idaho), powered directly by geothermal energy. This model was soon replicated in [Klamath Falls, Oregon](/Klamath_Falls,_Oregon), in 1900. The first building known to use geothermal energy as its primary heat source was the [Hot Lake Hotel](/Hot_Lake_Hotel) in [Union County, Oregon](/Union_County,_Oregon), starting in 1907. The applications broadened: a geothermal well was used to heat [greenhouses](/Greenhouses) in Boise in 1926, and around the same time, geysers were being harnessed for the same purpose in Iceland and [Tuscany](/Tuscany). In 1930, Charles Lieb developed the first [downhole heat exchanger](/Downhole_heat_changer) to heat his own home, a direct ancestor of modern systems. By 1943, Iceland was systematically using geyser steam and hot water to heat homes, a practice that would become central to its national identity.

A chart showing the slow, then accelerating, climb of global geothermal electric capacity. The upper red line marks installed capacity, while the lower green line shows what's actually produced.

The 20th century finally saw geothermal energy graduate to a source for electricity generation. On July 4, 1904, Prince [Piero Ginori Conti](/Piero_Ginori_Conti) tested the first geothermal power generator at the Larderello steam field. It was a modest success, managing to light four light bulbs—a flickering proof of concept. In 1911, this experiment culminated in the world's first commercial geothermal power plant built on the same site. For nearly half a century, it remained the sole industrial producer of geothermal electricity on the planet, until New Zealand finally built its own plant in 1958. By 2012, the Larderello field was producing some 594 megawatts.

In 1960, [Pacific Gas and Electric](/Pacific_Gas_and_Electric) initiated operations at the first U.S. geothermal power plant at [The Geysers](/The_Geysers) in California. The original turbine was a workhorse, lasting over 30 years and producing a steady 11 [MW](/Megawatt) of net power.

The binary cycle power station, which uses a secondary organic fluid, was first demonstrated in 1967 in the [USSR](/USSR) and was later introduced to the United States in 1981. This critical innovation allows for the use of much lower temperature resources, as low as 81 °C. Pushing this boundary further, a binary cycle plant in [Chena Hot Springs, Alaska](/Chena_Hot_Springs,_Alaska), came online in 2006, generating electricity from a record-low fluid temperature of just 57 °C (135 °F).

### Resources

A diagram of an enhanced geothermal system: 1:Reservoir 2:Pump house 3:Heat exchanger 4:Turbine hall 5:Production well 6:Injection well 7:Hot water to district heating 8:Porous sediments 9:Observation well 10:Crystalline bedrock. Essentially, a brute-force method of making the Earth give up its heat.

The Earth's core holds a staggering internal heat content of 10³¹ joules (or 3·10¹⁵ [TWh](/TWh)), a number so large it's practically meaningless. Roughly 20% of this is residual heat from the chaos of [planetary accretion](/Planetary_accretion), the cosmic debris slamming together to form our world. The rest is the product of past and ongoing [radioactive decay](/Radioactive_decay) of [naturally occurring isotopes](/Naturally_occurring_radioactive_material). For instance, a 5,275-meter-deep borehole for the United Downs Deep Geothermal Power Project in [Cornwall](/Cornwall), England, discovered granite with an unusually high concentration of [thorium](/Thorium). The slow, steady [radioactive decay](/Radioactive_decay) of this element is believed to be the power source for the rock's extreme temperature.

Deep inside the Earth, the temperature and pressure are immense enough to melt some rock and cause the solid [mantle](/Mantle_(geology)) to behave like a slow, thick plastic. Pockets of this mantle [convect](/Mantle_convection) upward, being lighter than the surrounding material. At the [core–mantle boundary](/Core%E2%80%93mantle_boundary), temperatures can exceed 4,000 °C (7,230 °F).

This internal thermal energy perpetually [flows to the surface via conduction](/Heat_flux) at a rate of 44.2 [terawatts](/Terawatts) (TW). It is simultaneously replenished by the radioactive decay of minerals at a rate of 30 TW. These power figures are more than double humanity's total current energy consumption from all sources combined. However, most of this energy flux is too diffuse and impractical to recover. In addition to this deep heat, the top 10 meters (33 ft) of the surface are subject to the whims of the sun, heating up in the summer and cooling in the winter.

Beneath this seasonal layer, the [geothermal gradient](/Geothermal_gradient)—the rate at which temperature increases with depth—is a relatively consistent 25–30 °C (77–86 °F) per kilometer of depth across most of the world. The conductive heat [flux](/Flux) averages 0.1 MW/km². These values spike dramatically near tectonic plate boundaries, where the crust is thinner. They can be further amplified by fluid circulation, through mechanisms like [magma conduits](/Magma_conduit), [hot springs](/Hot_springs), and [hydrothermal circulation](/Hydrothermal_circulation).

The efficiency and, more importantly, the profitability of electricity generation are acutely sensitive to temperature. The most lucrative applications draw from high natural heat flux, ideally from a [hot spring](/Hot_spring). The next best approach is drilling a well into a hot [aquifer](/Aquifer). Where nature doesn't provide a convenient reservoir, one can be created by injecting water to [hydraulically fracture](/Hydraulically_fracture) the bedrock. These manufactured systems are known as [enhanced geothermal systems](/Enhanced_geothermal_systems).

Estimates from 2010 regarding the potential for geothermal electricity generation vary wildly, from a modest 0.035 TW to an optimistic 2 TW, with the final figure depending entirely on the scale of investment. The higher estimates assume the feasibility of wells drilled to depths of 10 kilometers (6 mi), a significant leap from 20th-century wells that seldom exceeded 3 kilometers (2 mi). Wells of this depth are, however, commonplace in the petroleum industry, which has had far more money to throw at the problem of deep drilling.

### Geothermal power

*Main article: [Geothermal power](/Geothermal_power)*

Geothermal power is simply the [electrical power generated](/Electricity_generation) from geothermal energy. The primary methods for this conversion are dry steam, flash steam, and binary cycle power stations. As of 2010, geothermal electricity was being produced in 26 countries.

By 2019, the worldwide installed geothermal power capacity reached 15.4 [gigawatts](/Gigawatt) (GW). The [United States](/Geothermal_energy_in_the_United_States) accounted for the largest share, with 3.68 GW, or 23.86 percent of the global total.

In several countries, geothermal energy is not a niche player but a cornerstone of the national grid. It supplies a significant portion of the electrical power in [Iceland](/Geothermal_power_in_Iceland), [El Salvador](/Geothermal_power_in_El_Salvador), [Kenya](/Geothermal_power_in_Kenya), the [Philippines](/Geothermal_power_in_the_Philippines), and [New Zealand](/New_Zealand).

Geothermal power is classified as a [renewable](/Renewable_energy) energy source because the rate at which we extract heat is infinitesimal compared to the [Earth's total heat content](/Earth%27s_internal_heat_budget). The [greenhouse gas emissions](/Life-cycle_greenhouse-gas_emissions_of_energy_sources) from geothermal electric stations are, on average, 45 grams of [carbon dioxide](/Carbon_dioxide) per kilowatt-hour of electricity. This is less than 5 percent of the emissions from a typical coal-fired plant.

Traditionally, geothermal electric plants were constructed exclusively at the edges of tectonic plates, where high-temperature resources are conveniently close to the surface. An ideal site has high subsurface temperatures, high permeability, and a large nearby water reserve to act as a working fluid. The advent of [binary cycle power plants](/Binary_cycle_power_plant) and significant improvements in drilling and extraction technology are enabling [enhanced geothermal systems](/Enhanced_geothermal_systems) to be deployed over a much broader geographical range. Demonstration projects are currently operational in [Landau-Pfalz](/Landau-Pfalz), Germany, and [Soultz-sous-Forêts](/Soultz-sous-For%C3%AAts), France. An earlier effort in [Basel](/Basel), Switzerland, was notoriously shut down [after it triggered earthquakes](/Induced_seismicity_in_Basel). Other demonstration projects are under construction in [Australia](/Geothermal_power_in_Australia), the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom), and the US. In [Myanmar](/Myanmar), over 39 locations have been identified as capable of geothermal power production, with some conveniently located near major urban centers like [Yangon](/Yangon).

